  {
    "id": "ce2016-q063",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "operating-systems",
    "subtopic": "processes",
    "stem": "Single Processor means _____________________ .",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Perform only one process at a given time.",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Executes next process only after the current process is completed.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "No need for process scheduling in CPU.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "All of the above.",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "[CE] questions.pdf",
      "exam": "K-Companies",
      "year": 2016,
      "tier": "gold",
      "originalNumber": 63
    },
    "keyProvenance": "derived",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "5b799f740875952fc9b9cfc0dee520bbed8f47f3",
    "explanation": "Only A is true: a single processor can execute just one process at any given instant. B is false because a multiprogrammed OS preempts and time-slices, so the next process runs long before the current one finishes, and C is false and self-refuting since a single CPU is exactly the case that needs scheduling. Note the printed answer sheet keys D ('All of the above'), which cannot hold once B and C are false."
  },
  {
    "id": "ce2016-q064",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "operating-systems",
    "subtopic": "process-states",
    "stem": "In blocking state, we can find __________ .",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "The processes waiting for I/O.",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "The process that is running.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "The processes waiting for the processor.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "All of the above.",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "[CE] questions.pdf",
      "exam": "K-Companies",
      "year": 2016,
      "tier": "gold",
      "originalNumber": 64
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "20d5a77e218aa7aab3afd96b8312f7371b7eaf22",
    "explanation": "The blocked (waiting) state holds processes that cannot run until some external event completes, typically an I/O operation. Option C is the trap: a process waiting for the processor is in the Ready state, not blocked, because it needs nothing but the CPU."
  },
